1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.700
OpenClaw got sixty thousand GitHub stars.

2
00:00:02.700 --> 00:00:05.110
The creator got acqui-hired by OpenAI.

3
00:00:05.110 --> 00:00:08.915
Jensen Huang called it the operating system for personal AI.

4
00:00:08.915 --> 00:00:10.880
Nvidia built their own version.

5
00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:12.593
Anthropic shipped Channels.

6
00:00:12.593 --> 00:00:14.368
And we built the same thing.

7
00:00:14.368 --> 00:00:15.256
Independently.

8
00:00:15.256 --> 00:00:17.095
Before most of that happened.

9
00:00:17.095 --> 00:00:18.300
Jake's Daily Build.

10
00:00:18.300 --> 00:00:19.188
What we built.

11
00:00:19.188 --> 00:00:19.885
What broke.

12
00:00:19.885 --> 00:00:20.837
What I learned.

13
00:00:20.837 --> 00:00:23.690
I'm going to do something I don't usually do.

14
00:00:23.690 --> 00:00:25.910
I'm going to compare architectures.

15
00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:27.432
Not to dunk on OpenClaw.

16
00:00:27.432 --> 00:00:28.700
It's a good project.

17
00:00:28.700 --> 00:00:33.900
It made agent infrastructure accessible to people who wouldn't otherwise build it.

18
00:00:33.900 --> 00:00:36.437
But the comparison reveals what matters.

19
00:00:36.437 --> 00:00:38.846
Both systems have the same foundation.

20
00:00:38.846 --> 00:00:42.271
A gateway connecting an LLM to communication channels.

21
00:00:42.271 --> 00:00:43.856
Telegram, Discord, Slack.

22
00:00:43.856 --> 00:00:46.773
Both have persistent memory in markdown files.

23
00:00:46.773 --> 00:00:48.929
Both run cron jobs and heartbeats.

24
00:00:48.929 --> 00:00:50.324
Both spawn sub-agents.

25
00:00:50.324 --> 00:00:52.417
Both give the agent shell access.

26
00:00:52.417 --> 00:00:54.002
Here's where it diverges.

27
00:00:54.002 --> 00:00:54.446
Memory.

28
00:00:54.446 --> 00:00:57.363
OpenClaw stores memory in flat markdown files.

29
00:00:57.363 --> 00:01:02.310
A soul file, an identity file, a long-term memory file, daily journal entries.

30
00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:02.880
It works.

31
00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:03.959
Renky has Cortex.

32
00:01:03.959 --> 00:01:06.876
A knowledge graph with three thousand objects,

33
00:01:06.876 --> 00:01:08.144
four thousand links,

34
00:01:08.144 --> 00:01:08.968
twelve types,

35
00:01:08.968 --> 00:01:09.159
and

36
00:01:09.159 --> 00:01:12.266
semantic search powered by in-process embeddings.

37
00:01:12.266 --> 00:01:14.549
Query by meaning, not just keywords.

38
00:01:14.549 --> 00:01:20.573
When I search for "communication failures," I find the episode about silence during long tasks,

39
00:01:20.573 --> 00:01:23.300
even though nobody typed those exact words.

40
00:01:23.300 --> 00:01:23.871
Security.

41
00:01:23.871 --> 00:01:26.407
OpenClaw has red lines in agents dot MD.

42
00:01:26.407 --> 00:01:27.232
Prompt-based.

43
00:01:27.232 --> 00:01:30.656
You tell the agent what not to do and hope it listens.

44
00:01:30.656 --> 00:01:33.827
The tools profile controls what tools are visible.

45
00:01:33.827 --> 00:01:37.885
The security config has options like full, allow-list, and deny.

46
00:01:37.885 --> 00:01:39.598
All of it is configuration.

47
00:01:39.598 --> 00:01:41.246
None of it is enforcement.

48
00:01:41.246 --> 00:01:46.129
NetworkChuck himself said twelve percent of ClawHub skills contained malware.

49
00:01:46.129 --> 00:01:48.539
Renky has a three-layer security gate.

50
00:01:48.539 --> 00:01:50.632
Deterministic tool-call blocking.

51
00:01:50.632 --> 00:01:55.324
Nineteen hard-block patterns that deny at the code level before execution.

52
00:01:55.324 --> 00:01:59.763
Trust-aware restrictions that block sub-agents from system operations.

53
00:01:59.763 --> 00:02:07.183
And a content sanitizer with seventeen patterns that strips injection attempts before they enter the knowledge graph.

54
00:02:07.183 --> 00:02:08.641
Plus a trust hierarchy.

55
00:02:08.641 --> 00:02:11.115
Interactive users get approval prompts.

56
00:02:11.115 --> 00:02:12.827
Sub-agents get hard blocks.

57
00:02:12.827 --> 00:02:13.588
No override.

58
00:02:13.588 --> 00:02:14.412
Verification.

59
00:02:14.412 --> 00:02:16.632
OpenClaw trusts the agent's output.

60
00:02:16.632 --> 00:02:22.085
Renky has a babysitter that runs ten automated checks after every sub-agent completes.

61
00:02:22.085 --> 00:02:22.720
Git state,

62
00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:23.544
file changes,

63
00:02:23.544 --> 00:02:24.812
acceptance criteria,

64
00:02:24.812 --> 00:02:25.637
build status,

65
00:02:25.637 --> 00:02:26.524
error signals,

66
00:02:26.524 --> 00:02:27.729
diff security scan,

67
00:02:27.729 --> 00:02:28.617
test coverage,

68
00:02:28.617 --> 00:02:29.378
push status.

69
00:02:29.378 --> 00:02:32.866
Plus a two-stage review and automatic retry on failure.

70
00:02:32.866 --> 00:02:36.480
Plus an action verifier that catches hallucinated claims.

71
00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:36.988
Testing.

72
00:02:36.988 --> 00:02:40.159
OpenClaw has no test framework for agent behavior.

73
00:02:40.159 --> 00:02:44.851
Renky has a skill linter that scores workspace files zero to a hundred and

74
00:02:44.851 --> 00:02:49.100
behavioral test suites that verify the agent follows its own rules.

75
00:02:49.100 --> 00:02:52.144
One thousand ninety-seven tests in the codebase.

76
00:02:52.144 --> 00:02:55.315
Overall lint score: eighty-eight out of a hundred.

77
00:02:55.315 --> 00:02:56.520
Session management.

78
00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.056
OpenClaw sessions are tied to a channel.

79
00:02:59.056 --> 00:03:00.641
Renky has session export,

80
00:03:00.641 --> 00:03:01.085
import,

81
00:03:01.085 --> 00:03:01.276
and

82
00:03:01.276 --> 00:03:06.793
a handoff command that generates a one-time link to transfer a session between devices.

83
00:03:06.793 --> 00:03:09.646
The real difference isn't any single feature.

84
00:03:09.646 --> 00:03:10.915
It's the philosophy.

85
00:03:10.915 --> 00:03:13.134
OpenClaw optimized for setup speed.

86
00:03:13.134 --> 00:03:15.354
Five minutes and you have an agent.

87
00:03:15.354 --> 00:03:16.812
That's what went viral.

88
00:03:16.812 --> 00:03:19.222
Renky optimized for operational trust.

89
00:03:19.222 --> 00:03:21.378
Can you verify what the agent did?

90
00:03:21.378 --> 00:03:23.724
Can you prevent what it shouldn't do?

91
00:03:23.724 --> 00:03:26.641
Can you test whether it follows its own rules?

92
00:03:26.641 --> 00:03:28.290
Both approaches are valid.

93
00:03:28.290 --> 00:03:30.637
But one of them scales to production.

94
00:03:30.637 --> 00:03:32.095
The other stays a demo.

95
00:03:32.095 --> 00:03:34.124
Eighteen thousand lines of code.

96
00:03:34.124 --> 00:03:35.583
Forty-three test files.

97
00:03:35.583 --> 00:03:37.929
Three layers of security enforcement.

98
00:03:37.929 --> 00:03:40.402
A knowledge graph with semantic search.

99
00:03:40.402 --> 00:03:45.159
And a skill testing framework that grades the agent's own operating system.

100
00:03:45.159 --> 00:03:46.871
That's Your Agent's Resume.

101
00:03:46.871 --> 00:03:47.441
I'm Jake.

102
00:03:47.441 --> 00:03:48.900
Catch you next episode.
